FeedPackage.Description:
Store nearly anything instantly and easily, without the need of a database server. All you need to access to the folder where the data is stored. This is great for tiny applications, or giant enterprise applications because it scales from a single machine almost to infinity, with almost no degradation in performance from the first record to the trillionth. You can have as many nodes as can share a file (almost limitless), as many records as disk can hold (this grows every year), as much Sharding of data as folder structures allow (again, almost limitless). From a scaling perspective, it is very robust. The very granular, performant approach used removes almost all limits to size, accessibility and availability. The limits are controlled by the infrastructure and not by ZarahDB. If the OS can reach the file, ZarahDB can work with it.
OpenSource code at https://github.com/MikeReedKS/ZarahDB
FeedPackage.ReleaseNotes: Initial Private Release - Not yet ready for prime time. It is highly useable, but source code it not yet available and neither is support. Nothing is yet written in stone. No promises of future compatibility are assured. None the less, it is cool, new and so bloody fast and easy, it might be worth a few minutes to check it out!

FeedPackage.Description: * Allows you to Subscribe to a queue instead of polling it in a busy loop. That is, you provide a delegate function in “Subscribe” method and this callback will be invoked every time a new message is added to the queue. This library will also handle serialization and deserialization for your objects that you put in the queue. * Also, optionally, would automatically delete messages from the queue once they processed successfully, which is not done by the AWS SDK library. * It creates a new queue either in Send or in Subscribe if the queue with the given name doesn’t exist yet under your account on AWS. Small and Simple. Requires AWSSDK.SQS, Newtonsof.Json and log4net.
FeedPackage.ReleaseNotes: * Added CLSCompliant. * Added ISqsSubscriber interface to allow for unit-testing with mocking * Added error handling in subscibe * Updated to the latest version of AWSSDK.SQS * Support .NET Core
FeedPackage.Tags: SQS AWS Amazon queue event delegate .NET Core
